article.description: Texas is on a roll into what promises to be a tough month of December.
article.headline: Longhorns roll over Bobcats
article.linkText: Texas holds Texas State to nine in second half
article.story:
AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas is on a roll into what promises to be
a tough month of December.

Stacy Stephens scored 19 points and the No. 2 Longhorns routed
Texas State 88-27 Wednesday night, setting a school record by
holding the Bobcats to nine points in the second half.

Texas (7-0) has won its last five games by an average of 40.4
points. Tiffany Jackson added 18 points for the Longhorns.

The next three weeks will get much tougher on the road. The
Longhorns travel to No. 8 Penn State on Sunday before games later
this month against No. 11 Georgia at home and back on the road
against No. 3 Tennessee.

"We've got to get ready to play on the road, our toughest
opponent yet on their home floor. A lot of teams that go up to
Happy Valley don't leave very happy," Texas coach Jody Conradt
said.

The Longhorns were glad to have a breather against the Bobcats
(0-5).

Coming off a long Thanksgiving weekend trip to Hawaii to win the
Rainbow Wahine Classic tournament, Texas shot 61 percent from the
floor, won the rebounding 49-20 and held Texas State to 3-of-29
shooting in the second half.

The nine points allowed in the second half broke the Texas
record of 13 accomplished twice, the last time against Texas Tech
in 1979. It also tied the fewest points allowed in any half, set
against Rice in 1990.

"We were pretty over overpowering," Conradt said.

Ally Kelly scored eight points to lead Texas State (0-5), which
committed 25 turnovers.

"I think it's embarrassing," said Bobcats center Tori Talbert,
who came in averaging 15.5 points but was overwhelmed by Stephens'
strength and Jackson's athleticism under the basket.

Texas led 45-18 at halftime behind 63-percent shooting and 42
points in the paint.

Stephens was 9-of-10 from the floor and hit all five of her
attempts in the first half -- nearly all of them layups on easy
turnarounds in the post -- and Conradt subbed early and often to
experiment with different lineups.

"We need to develop depth," Conradt said. "We'll need other
players down the line."

By the time the score was 25-5 with 11 minutes left in the half,
the Longhorns started passing up some open shots in favor of
dumping the ball down low or driving for easy layups.

Jackson was nearly as dominating as Stephens, going 8-of-11 from
the floor.

Stephens joked that her only miss was intentional.

"I've got to give the coaches something to gripe about," she
said.
